    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter April 22nd with a high-ceiling lineup led by **Yordan Alvarez** (73.68) and **Kyle Schwarber** (69.68). **Yordan Alvarez** benefits from a strong platoon advantage against the right-handed Bibee, while **Kyle Schwarber** finds himself in an ideal spot against Matthew Boyd; his elite xwOBA of 0.402 combined with a favorable park and prime #2 order placement makes him one of the safest bets on the board. **Trea Turner** (69.03) also grades out as a elite play, with his top-of-the-order responsibilities and stolen base potential outweighing the slight penalty for facing a southpaw in Boyd. **Junior Caminero** (62.35) rounds out our top-tier starts, leveraging a high base projection that successfully mitigates his negative park variance.\n\nWe are navigating several critical platoon edges to maintain our efficiency. **Colt Keith** (57.81) and **Luke Raley** (54.70) both see substantial upward adjustments due to favorable R/R or platoon splits, helping them secure starting spots despite mediocre SP_xERA matchups. Conversely, the optimizer was forced to make a tough call on **Caleb Durbin** (46.25), who narrowly missed the starting cut. While **Caleb Durbin** offers elite stolen base upside, the volatility of facing an elite arm like Max Fried, coupled with a bottom-third lineup position, pushed his efficiency score just below the threshold required to displace **Victor Scott II** or **Pete Crow-Armstrong**. \n\nRisk management remains a priority today, as most of our projected lineup relies on \"Lineup Pending\" status, which introduces volatility regarding final batting order placement. **Dillon Dingler** (41.22) is particularly sensitive to these fluctuations; should he drop lower than the assumed #5 spot, his score could dip toward the marginal zone. Furthermore, the defensive efficiency of opposing catchers is a recurring theme today, specifically penalizing the scores for **Pete Crow-Armstrong** and **Hyeseong Kim**. We are 